		<h4><div>An early Christmas gift<br>&mdash; wrapped in baroque music</div></h4>
		<p>What would you like for Christmas?</p>
		<p>How &lsquo;bout Winnipeg&rsquo;s foremost baroque vocal ensemble and &ldquo;Canada&rsquo;s tiny, perfect orchestra&rdquo; conducted by this country&rsquo;s leading interpreter of choral and operatic repertoire?</p>
		<p>Guest conductor David Fallis specializes in the music of the baroque and classical periods &mdash; perfect for this program of festive early music treasures.</p>
		<p>We will hear works from five 17th-century composers &mdash; three of them Italian, one French and one Czechoslovakian.</p>
		<p>Buon Natale! Joyeux No&euml;l! Vesel&eacute; v&aacute;noce!</p>
		<p><b>Curated by a friend, for friends</b></p>
		<p>When you combine the MCO strings with the voices of Canzona in the intimate acoustic splendour of Westminster Church, you get magic! And the magician in charge of this production is none other than local early music specialist Eric Lussier.</p>
		<p>After choosing a selection of instrumental works from the baroque library he donated to the MCO, Eric turned to Canzona&rsquo;s Artistic Director Henry Engbrecht, who recommended that the <i>Zelenka Te Deum</i> close the concert.</p>
		<p>&ldquo;I have yet to be disappointed at a Canzona concert ... due in great part to the longtime expert musical direction and unflagging dedication of Henry Engbrecht&rdquo; &mdash; Gwenda Nemerofsky, Winnipeg Free Press.</p>

