			<div class="tab-pane fade" id="notes">
				<p><b>Concerto grosso in C Major, Op. 3 No. 12<br>&mdash; &lsquo;Per il santissimo natale&rsquo;<br>Francesco Onofrio Manfredini</b></p>
				<p>Manfredini was one of the many gifted eighteenth-century Italian composers who worked in a variety of cities and towns throughout the country. Born in Pistoia, he undertook his musical studies in Bologna with the eminent composer Giuseppe Torelli. He later resided in several cities, including Ferrara, where he occupied the positions of violinist and director of music for various courts and churches. In 1711, he relocated to Monaco, where he was active as a composer and performer of instrumental music. In 1724, he returned to Pistoia to become director of music at the cathedral, and he remained in that position for the rest of his life. Much of his large output of music has disappeared, including nine oratorios that won considerable success during his lifetime.</p>
				<p>His Opus 3, consisting of 12 concerti grossi for strings, was published in Bologna in 1718. Manfredini dedicated it to Prince Antoine I, his employer in Monaco. The concerto grosso (grand concerto), one of the Baroque era&rsquo;s most popular forms, is founded on the interplay between two bodies of strings: a small concertino (usually two violins and a cello), and a larger group, the ripieno. Two of its major early exponents were Giuseppe Torelli and Arcangelo Corelli. </p>
				<p>This attractive Christmas concerto is the last piece in Manfredini&rsquo;s Opus 3 collection. It opens with a gently lilting siciliano suggesting the peaceful life of shepherds and the quiet joy of Christ&rsquo;s birth. This is followed by a slow, mournful Largo, and an energetic finale. </p>
				<p><b>No&euml;ls pour les instruments<br>(Christmas Melodies for Instruments)<br>Marc-Antoine Charpentier</b></p>
				<ol>
					<li>Les bourgeois de Ch&acirc;tre 1</li>
					<li>Joseph est bien mari&eacute;</li>
					<li>Or nous dites, Marie</li>
					<li>Laissez pa&icirc;tre vos b&ecirc;tes</li>
					<li>Vous que d&eacute;sirez sans fin</li>
					<li>&Aacute; la venue de No&euml;l</li>
					<li>O Cr&eacute;ateur</li>
					<li>Une jeune pucelle</li>
					<li>O&ugrave; s&rsquo;en vont ces gais bergers?</li>
					<li>Les bourgeois de Ch&acirc;tre 2</li>
				</ol>
				<p>French composer Charpentier was best known during his lifetime for his theatre scores &mdash; including incidental music for plays by the renowned writer Molière, plus more than a dozen operas &mdash; and for his sacred choral music. Among the latter type of piece his several settings of the <i>Te Deum</i> (Thou God) text stand out.</p>
				<p>Several French composers of the Baroque period created no&euml;ls, instrumental settings of traditional melodies associated with Christmas. In their settings for organ or harpsichord, French composers of a slightly later time than Charpentier&rsquo;s, such as Louis-Claude Daquin, Jean-Fran&ccedil;ois Dandrieu, Claude Balbastre and Nicolas Leb&egrave;gue, used them as points of departure to demonstrate their virtuosity as performers. </p>
				<p>Charpentier adopted a different, more reserved approach. In the no&euml;l settings for instrumental ensemble that you will hear at this concert, he left the melodies virtually in their pristine original state. His contribution was to envelop them in the most delightful and refined of accompaniments. The brief pieces range in character from slow and expressive (<i>Or nous dites, Marie</i>) to quick and joyous (<i>Les bourgeois de Ch&acirc;tre</i>; <i>O&egrave; s&rsquo;en vont ces gais bergers?</i>). He also quoted them in his celebrated <i>Messe de minuit pour No&euml;l</i> (Midnight Mass for Christmas).</p>
				<p><b>Concerto grosso in G Min, Op. 6 No. 8 &mdash; &lsquo;Per la notte di Natale&rsquo;<br>Arcangelo Corelli</b></p>
				<p>Corelli&rsquo;s reputation and influence extended through much of Europe. This Italian musician was one of the leading violin soloists of the Baroque era, as well as a composer of music that is both appealing and historically significant. His sonatas for violin, for example, helped establish this instrument as the most important non-vocal element in music, and he played a major role in establishing the concerto grosso.</p>
				<p>Corelli&rsquo;s Opus 6 (1714), his final published work, is a set of 12 Concerti grossi. No. 8 has long been the best-known of the set. All of the movements except the last present the array of brief sections in contrasting moods and tempos that was typical of the concerto grosso. It is only the soothing, almost lullaby-like concluding pastorale that has specific associations with Christmas.</p>
				<p><b>Introduttiono teatralo in G Major, Op. 4, No. 4<br>Pietro Antonio Locatelli</b></p>
				<p>It was long thought that Locatelli had studied with Corelli, his fellow Italian, but it seems more likely that he was a follower of the older master&rsquo;s style rather than an actual student. He won his first fame as a violinist in Rome, then relocated several times to major cities in northern Italy, Germany and Prussia, everywhere winning high acclaim for his playing. He arrived in the Netherlands in 1729, there to remain for the rest of his life. </p>
				<p>With his probing creative imagination and fearless virtuoso performing style, he served as a model for the later Romantic school of music (ex. Paganini). &ldquo;He plays with so much fury upon his fiddle, that in my humble opinion, he must wear out some dozens of them in a year,&rdquo; wrote an Englishman who heard him play. And the <i>New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians</i> says of him, &ldquo;The 12 violin concertos that make up his <i>L&rsquo;arte del violino</i> (The Art of the Violin, 1733) had an immense influence on the development of violin technique, especially in France, where violin teaching continued to bear signs of his style of virtuosity until the beginning of the nineteenth century, and he also left a body of work whose idiom reflects aspects of the most advanced style of the day.&rdquo;</p>
				<p>His twelve Concerti grossi, Opus 1, were published in 1721. In them, he intensified the textures and broadened the colours of the form by adding violas to the concertino. Published in 1735 and dedicated to one of Amsterdam&rsquo;s richest merchants, Abraham Vermeeren, Locatelli&rsquo;s Opus 4 is scored for strings and consists of two parts: six &lsquo;Theatrical Introductions&rsquo; and six concerti. It is unclear if he literally intended the Introductions as preludes to operas, ballets or plays, or as concert works in similar style. They are hybrid works. In form, they follow the pattern of the Neopolitan opera overture, cast in three sections of fast, slow, and fast tempos, but in their scoring for two string ensembles they follow the concerto grosso model.</p>
				<p>The fourth Introduction is a most compact piece, its three movements lasting barely four minutes. The first is brisk and features plentiful interactions between the two sub-groups of the ensemble. The music slips into the minor mode for the slow and thoughtful second movement, to which Locatelli gave the description &lsquo;sempre piano&rsquo; (always quiet). The piece concludes with a joyous, playfully dance-like finale.</p>
				<p><b>Te Deum in D Major, ZWV 145<br>Jan Dismas Zelenka</b></p>
				<p><b>Part One</b></p>
				<ol>
					<li>Te Deum laudamus</li>
					<li>Sanctus</li>
					<li>Pleni sunt caeli et terra</li>
					<li>Te gloriosus Apostolorum chorus</li>
					<li>Tu ad liberandum</li>
					<li>Judex crederis esse venturus</li>
					<li>Aeterna fac</li>
				</ol>
				<p><b>Part Two</b></p>
				<ol>
					<li>Salvum fac populum tuum</li>
					<li>Et rege eos</li>
					<li>Per singulos dies</li>
					<li>Dignare Domine I</li>
					<li>Dignare Domine II</li>
					<li>Miserere</li>
					<li>In te Domine speravi</li>
				</ol>
				<p>Son of a Bohemian village choirmaster and organist, Zelenka moved from his home town, Louoňvice pod Blaníkem, northwest to nearby Prague to undertake his education at a Jesuit school. The earliest recorded performances of his music date from that period of study. He performed on the violone (the ancestor of the double bass) in service to Baron Hartig, the imperial governor resident in Prague.</p>
				<p>He relocated to Dresden, Germany about 1710, as a member of the Imperial Court Orchestra that was maintained by Augustus (known as &lsquo;The Strong&rsquo;), King of Poland and Elector of Saxony. Some accounts suggest that Zelenka had been forced to leave Bohemia in haste, but no solid evidence has surfaced to confirm that, or to give a reason for his doing so. Between 1716 and 1719 he traveled as far as Italy and Vienna in order to continue his studies. The celebrated composer Johann Fux was one of his teachers in Vienna. </p>
				<p>He then returned to Dresden. In 1723 he provided music (an incidental score to accompany a ‘melodrama&rsquo;) that was performed in conjunction with a significant state occasion: the celebrations that took place in Prague to mark the coronation of Charles VI and Elizabeth Christine as king and queen of Bohemia. It was reported that Zelenka&rsquo;s music (both choral and instrumental) drew higher praise than the compositions that Fux had composed for the same event. </p>
				<p>Johann Heinichen, the music director of the Dresden Royal Chapel, died in 1729. Zelenka took over many of his duties, but when the time came to appoint his official successor, Zelenka was passed over in favour of the hugely popular German opera composer, Johann Adolf Hasse. This choice reflected the court&rsquo;s greater interest in opera than in the liturgical music that had become Zelenka&rsquo;s forte. He received the appointment of Composer of the Royal Court Capelle instead.</p> 
				<p>His profound disappointment with this professional snub resulted in his compositional output falling off markedly throughout the 16 remaining years of his life. A posthumous tribute referred to him as &ldquo;a respectable, quiet, unassuming man, deserving of the greatest respect.&rdquo;</p>
				<p>After his death, his music was guarded carefully by the Dresden Court, which considered it a valuable state asset. It only began to see the light of day again in the 1860s, when the celebrated Bohemian composer Bedřich Smetana introduced one of his orchestral suites in Prague. The real breakthrough didn&rsquo;t come until nearly a century later. During the 1950s, the music began to be published and recorded, which led to it finally receiving the attention and esteem it clearly deserved.</p>
				<p>The majority of his 200-plus compositions are sacred choral works, in which he responded to the texts in consistently sensitive and imaginative ways. His music also displays a thorough mastery of counterpoint (a specialty of his teacher, Fux), the simultaneous combination of multiple musical lines. It earned the admiration of such major contemporary composers as Johann Sebastian Bach (who had his son, Wilhelm Friedemann, copy out part of a Zelenka composition in order to have it performed under Johann Sebastian&rsquo;s direction in a Leipzig church) and Georg Philipp Telemann. It contains numerous unorthodox structures and names, the latter including an instrumental piece that he mysteriously entitled <i>Hipocondrie</i>.</p>
				<p>As a condition for becoming king of Poland, Augustus the Strong had converted to Catholicism. He had a Catholic chapel constructed at the Dresden court. Zelenka was deeply involved in providing it with music, his own and that of other composers. Among the sacred choral works he composed for the king&rsquo;s chapel were two settings of a well-known liturgical text: <i>Te Deum</i> (Thou God). At this concert you will hear the first of them, which he composed c. 1724 (the second, also in D Major, followed in 1731). </p>
				<p>The text dates back as far as the sixth century. No definitive source has yet been determined. The most likely authors are a pair of saints, St. Ambrose and St. Augustine, as well as the Yugoslavian cleric Niceta of Remesiana. It has been sung in a variety of settings: as part of the Matins ceremony, as a processional chant, at the conclusion of liturgical dramas, and as either a song of thanksgiving or a hymn of victory on the battlefield. Musical settings by particular composers date back as far as Palestrina and include versions by Taverner, Lassus, Lully, Purcell, Handel, Haydn, Berlioz, Bruckner, Verdi, Dvo&#345;&aacute;k, Kod&acute;ly and Walton. </p>
				<p>In this <i>Te Deum</i>, Zelenka reused thematic material from the coronation ‘melodrama&rsquo; mentioned above. It has 14 short brief sections: 10 choruses, two solo arias, a duet, and a Gregorian intonation, Salvum fac, which appears at the beginning of the second half, after the consecration of the Eucharist. Much of Zelenka&rsquo;s score is suitably festive and jubilant in nature, with trumpets and timpani bolstering and brightening the texture. He provided contrast through several deeply expressive choruses in slow tempo. The score concludes with an impressive and uplifting fugue. </p>

